					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Sta=
tistical hypothesis test</div>
<p><b>Student's <i>t</i>-test</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Statistical_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical test">sta=
tistical test</a> used to test whether the difference between the response =
of two groups is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_signi=
ficance" title=3D"Statistical significance">statistically significant</a> o=
r not. It is any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_hypot=
hesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical hypothesis testin=
g">statistical hypothesis test</a> in which the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Test_statistic" title=3D"Test statistic">test statistic</a> f=
ollows a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-distributio=
n" title=3D"Student's t-distribution">Student's <i>t</i>-distribution</a> u=
nder the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Null_hypothesis" title=3D=
"Null hypothesis">null hypothesis</a>. It is most commonly applied when the=
 test statistic would follow a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nor=
mal_distribution" title=3D"Normal distribution">normal distribution</a> if =
the value of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scale_parameter" ti=
tle=3D"Scale parameter">scaling term</a> in the test statistic were known (=
typically, the scaling term is unknown and is therefore a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuisance_parameter" title=3D"Nuisance parameter">nu=
isance parameter</a>). When the scaling term is estimated based on the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data" title=3D"Data">data</a>, the tes=
t statistic=E2=80=94under certain conditions=E2=80=94follows a Student's <i=
>t</i> distribution. The <i>t</i>-test's most common application is to test=
 whether the means of two populations are significantly different. In many =
cases, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-test" title=3D"Z-test">=
<i>Z</i>-test</a> will yield very similar results to a <i>t</i>-test becaus=
e the latter converges to the former as the size of the dataset increases.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:William_Sealy_Gosset.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-de=
scription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb=
/4/42/William_Sealy_Gosset.jpg/250px-William_Sealy_Gosset.jpg" decoding=3D"=
async" width=3D"190" height=3D"245" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-wid=
th=3D"2000" data-file-height=3D"2577"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Sealy_Gosset" title=3D"William Sealy Gosset">Wi=
lliam Sealy Gosset</a>, who developed the "<i>t</i>-statistic" and publishe=
d it under the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pseudonym" title=3D=
"Pseudonym">pseudonym</a> of "Student"</figcaption></figure>
<p>The term "<i>t</i>-statistic" is abbreviated from "hypothesis test stati=
stic".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In statistics, th=
e <i>t</i>-distribution was first derived as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Posterior_probability" title=3D"Posterior probability">posteri=
or distribution</a> in 1876 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fri=
edrich_Robert_Helmert" title=3D"Friedrich Robert Helmert">Helmert</a><sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#=
cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-4"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacob_L%C3%BCroth" title=3D"=
Jacob L=C3=BCroth">L=C3=BCroth</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-5"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stud=
ent%27s_t-test#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <i>t</i>-distribution also appea=
red in a more general form as Pearson type&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pearson_distribution" title=3D"Pearson distribution">IV</a> d=
istribution in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" title=
=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a>'s 1895 paper.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test=
#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> However, the <i>t</i>-distribution, also known as =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-distribution" title=
=3D"Student's t-distribution">Student's <i>t</i>-distribution</a>, gets its=
 name from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Sealy_Gosset" t=
itle=3D"William Sealy Gosset">William Sealy Gosset</a>, who first published=
 it in English in 1908 in the scientific journal <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Biometrika" title=3D"Biometrika">Biometrika</a> using the ps=
eudonym "Student"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Probable_Error_of_a_Mean_9-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test=
#cite_note-The_Probable_Error_of_a_Mean-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> because his employer =
preferred staff to use <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pen_name" t=
itle=3D"Pen name">pen names</a> when publishing scientific papers.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Gosset worked at the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guinness_Brewery" title=3D"Guinness Brew=
ery">Guinness Brewery</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dubli=
n" title=3D"Dublin">Dublin</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ir=
eland" title=3D"Ireland">Ireland</a>, and was interested in the problems of=
 small samples&nbsp;=E2=80=93  for example, the chemical properties of barl=
ey with small sample sizes. Hence a second version of the etymology of the =
term Student is that Guinness did not want their competitors to know that t=
hey were using the <i>t</i>-test to determine the quality of raw material. =
Although it was William Gosset after whom the term "Student" is penned, it =
was actually through the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
onald_Fisher" title=3D"Ronald Fisher">Ronald Fisher</a> that the distributi=
on became well known as "Student's distribution"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-tes=
t#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> and "Student's <i>t</i>-test".
</p><p>Gosset devised the <i>t</i>-test as an economical way to monitor the=
 quality of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stout" title=3D"Stout"=
>stout</a>. The <i>t</i>-test work was submitted to and accepted in the jou=
rnal <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biometrika" title=3D"Biome=
trika">Biometrika</a></i> and published in 1908.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_Pro=
bable_Error_of_a_Mean_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-The_Probable_Error_of_a_Mean-9"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p>Guinness had a policy of allowing technical staff leave for study (s=
o-called "study leave"), which Gosset used during the first two terms of th=
e 1906=E2=80=931907 academic year in Professor <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Karl_Pearson" title=3D"Karl Pearson">Karl Pearson</a>'s Biomet=
ric Laboratory at <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_Colle=
ge_London" title=3D"University College London">University College London</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Gosset's identity =
was then known to fellow statisticians and to editor-in-chief Karl Pearson.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dodge2008_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Dodge2008-13"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
