<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Two-sample_t-tests">Two-sam=
ple <i>t</i>-tests</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?t=
itle=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit =
section: Two-sample t-tests"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Type_1_error.png" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/Ty=
pe_1_error.png/250px-Type_1_error.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" hei=
ght=3D"182" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"598" data-file-hei=
ght=3D"435"></a><figcaption>Type I error of unpaired and paired two-sample =
<i>t</i>-tests as a function of the correlation. The simulated random numbe=
rs originate from a bivariate normal distribution with a variance of 1. The=
 significance level is 5% and the number of cases is 60.</figcaption></figu=
re>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Power_of_t-tests.png" class=3D"mw-file-descri=
ption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5=
7/Power_of_t-tests.png/250px-Power_of_t-tests.png" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"182" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"598" d=
ata-file-height=3D"435"></a><figcaption>Power of unpaired and paired two-sa=
mple <i>t</i>-tests as a function of the correlation. The simulated random =
numbers originate from a bivariate normal distribution with a variance of 1=
 and a deviation of the expected value of 0.4. The significance level is 5%=
 and the number of cases is 60.</figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>two-sample</b> location test of the null hypothesis such that the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expected_value" title=3D"Expected v=
alue">means</a> of two populations are equal. All such tests are usually ca=
lled <b>Student's <i>t</i>-tests</b>, though strictly speaking that name sh=
ould only be used if the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance"=
 title=3D"Variance">variances</a> of the two populations are also assumed t=
o be equal; the form of the test used when this assumption is dropped is so=
metimes called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welch%27s_t_test" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Welch's t test">Welch's <i>t</i>-test</a>. Th=
ese tests are often referred to as <b>unpaired</b> or <i>independent sample=
s</i> <i>t</i>-tests, as they are typically applied when the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Unit (statistics)">statistical units</a> underlying the two samples bei=
ng compared are non-overlapping.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-fadem_14-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_n=
ote-fadem-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Two-sample <i>t</i>-tests for a difference in means involve independ=
ent samples (unpaired samples) or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Paired_sample" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Paired sample">paired samples=
</a>.  Paired <i>t</i>-tests are a form of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Blocking_(statistics)" title=3D"Blocking (statistics)">blocking</a=
>, and have greater <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_po=
wer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical power">power</a> (probabili=
ty of avoiding a type II error, also known as a false negative) than unpair=
ed tests when the paired units are similar with respect to "noise factors" =
(see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confounder" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Confounder">confounder</a>) that are independent of membershi=
p in the two groups being compared.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-1=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> In a different context, paired <i>t</i>-tests can be used to=
 reduce the effects of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Confounders=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Confounders">confounding factors</a> in an=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observational_study" title=3D"Obs=
ervational study">observational study</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Independent_(unpaired)_samp=
les"><span id=3D"Independent_.28unpaired.29_samples"></span>Independent (un=
paired) samples</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit sec=
tion: Independent (unpaired) samples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The independent samples <i>t</i>-test is used when two separate sets of =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Independent_and_identically-distri=
buted_random_variables" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Independent and iden=
tically-distributed random variables">independent and identically distribut=
ed</a> samples are obtained, and one variable from each of the two populati=
ons is compared. For example, suppose we are evaluating the effect of a med=
ical treatment, and we enroll 100&nbsp;subjects into our study, then random=
ly assign 50&nbsp;subjects to the treatment group and 50&nbsp;subjects to t=
he control group. In this case, we have two independent samples and would u=
se the unpaired form of the <i>t</i>-test.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Paired_samples">Paired samp=
les</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStudent%=
27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Paired=
 samples"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paired_difference_test" title=3D=
"Paired difference test">Paired difference test</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paired_sample" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Paired sample">Paired samples</a> <i>t</i>-tests typically c=
onsist of a sample of matched pairs of similar <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Unit_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Unit (statis=
tics)">units</a>, or one group of units that has been tested twice (a "repe=
ated measures" <i>t</i>-test).
</p><p>A typical example of the repeated measures <i>t</i>-test would be wh=
ere subjects are examined prior to a treatment, say for high blood pressure=
, and the same subjects are examined again after treatment with a blood-pre=
ssure-lowering medication. By comparing the same patient's numbers before a=
nd after treatment, we are effectively using each patient as their own cont=
rol. That way the correct rejection of the null hypothesis (here: of no dif=
ference made by the treatment) can become much more likely, with statistica=
l power increasing simply because the random inter-patient variation has no=
w been eliminated. However, an increase of statistical power comes at a pri=
ce: more examinations are required, each subject having to be examined twic=
e.
</p><p>Because half of the sample now depends on the other half, the paired=
 version of Student's <i>t</i>-test has only <span class=3D"texhtml"><span =
class=3D"sfrac">=E2=81=A0<span class=3D"tion"><span class=3D"num"><i>n</i><=
/span><span class=3D"sr-only">/</span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>=
=E2=81=A0</span> =E2=88=92 1</span> degrees of freedom (with <span class=3D=
"texhtml"><i>n</i></span> being the total number of observations). Pairs be=
come individual test units, and the sample has to be doubled to achieve the=
 same number of degrees of freedom. Normally, there are <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>n</i> =E2=88=92 1</span> degrees of freedom (with <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>n</i></span> being the total number of observations).<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St=
udent%27s_t-test#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A paired samples <i>t</i>-test based on a "matched-pairs sample" res=
ults from an unpaired sample that is subsequently used to form a paired sam=
ple, by using additional variables that were measured along with the variab=
le of interest.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The m=
atching is carried out by identifying pairs of values consisting of one obs=
ervation from each of the two samples, where the pair is similar in terms o=
f other measured variables. This approach is sometimes used in observationa=
l studies to reduce or eliminate the effects of confounding factors.
</p><p>Paired samples <i>t</i>-tests are often referred to as "dependent sa=
mples <i>t</i>-tests".
</p>
