<p>Most test statistics have the form <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i> =3D =
<i>Z</i>/<i>s</i></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Z</i></span> and=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> are functions of the data.
</p><p><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Z</i></span> may be sensitive to the alte=
rnative hypothesis (i.e., its magnitude tends to be larger when the alterna=
tive hypothesis is true), whereas <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i></span> i=
s a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scale_parameter" title=3D"Scal=
e parameter">scaling parameter</a> that allows the distribution of <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml"><i>t</i></span> to be determined.
</p><p>As an example, in the one-sample <i>t</i>-test
</p>
