span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BC</i></span> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Population_mean" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Population=
 mean">population mean</a>.
</p><p>The assumptions underlying a <i>t</i>-test in the simplest form abov=
e are that:
</p>
<ul><li><span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"text-decoration:overline;"><=
i>X</i></span></span> follows a normal distribution with mean <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BC</i></span> and variance <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
=CF=83</i><sup>2</sup>/<i>n</i></span>.</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>s</i><sup>2</sup>(<i>n</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nb=
sp;1)/<i>=CF=83</i><sup>2</sup></span> follows a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Chi-squared_distribution" title=3D"Chi-squared distribution"=
><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=87</i><sup>2</sup></span> distribution</a> =
with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;1</span> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degrees_of_freedom_(statistics)" title=3D=
"Degrees of freedom (statistics)">degrees of freedom</a>. This assumption i=
s met when the observations used for estimating <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
s</i><sup>2</sup></span> come from a normal distribution (and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/I.i.d." class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"I.i.d.">=
i.i.d.</a> for each group).</li>
<li><span class=3D"texhtml"><i>Z</i></span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
s</i></span> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_indep=
endence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statistical independence">independe=
nt</a>.</li></ul>
<p>In the <i>t</i>-test comparing the means of two independent samples, the=
 following assumptions should be met:
</p>
<ul><li>The means of the two populations being compared should follow <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normal_distributions" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Normal distributions">normal distributions</a>. Under weak as=
sumptions, this follows in large samples from the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Central limit theorem">cent=
ral limit theorem</a>, even when the distribution of observations in each g=
roup is non-normal.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-:0-18"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup></li>
<li>If using Student's original definition of the <i>t</i>-test, the two po=
pulations being compared should have the same variance (testable using <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F-test_of_equality_of_variances" title=
=3D"F-test of equality of variances"><i>F</i>-test</a>, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Levene%27s_test" title=3D"Levene's test">Levene's tes=
t</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bartlett%27s_test" title=3D=
"Bartlett's test">Bartlett's test</a>, or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Brown%E2%80%93Forsythe_test" title=3D"Brown=E2=80=93Forsythe te=
st">Brown=E2=80=93Forsythe test</a>; or assessable graphically using a <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q%E2%80%93Q_plot" title=3D"Q=E2=80=93Q=
 plot">Q=E2=80=93Q plot</a>). If the sample sizes in the two groups being c=
ompared are equal, Student's original <i>t</i>-test is highly robust to the=
 presence of unequal variances.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-19"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welch%27s_t-test" title=
=3D"Welch's t-test">Welch's <i>t</i>-test</a> is insensitive to equality of=
 the variances regardless of whether the sample sizes are similar.</li>
<li>The data used to carry out the test should either be sampled independen=
tly from the two populations being compared or be fully paired. This is in =
general not testable from the data, but if the data are known to be depende=
nt (e.g. paired by test design), a dependent test has to be applied. For pa=
rtially paired data, the classical independent <i>t</i>-tests may give inva=
lid results as the test statistic might not follow a <i>t</i> distribution,=
 while the dependent <i>t</i>-test is sub-optimal as it discards the unpair=
ed data.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Guo2017_20-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Guo2017-20"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li></ul>
<p>Most two-sample <i>t</i>-tests are robust to all but large deviations fr=
om the assumptions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Bland1995_21-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Bland=
1995-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exact_test" title=3D"Ex=
act test">exactness</a>, the <i>t</i>-test and <i>Z</i>-test require normal=
ity of the sample means, and the <i>t</i>-test additionally requires that t=
he sample variance follows a scaled <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Chi-squared_distribution" title=3D"Chi-squared distribution"><i>=CF=87</i=
><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span> distribution</a>,=
 and that the sample mean and sample variance be <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Independence_(probability_theory)" title=3D"Independence (pr=
obability theory)">statistically independent</a>.  Normality of the individ=
ual data values is not required if these conditions are met. By the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_limit_theorem" title=3D"Central l=
imit theorem">central limit theorem</a>, sample means of moderately large s=
amples are often well-approximated by a normal distribution even if the dat=
a are not normally distributed. However, the sample size required for the s=
ample means to converge to normality depends on the skewness of the distrib=
ution of the original data. The sample can vary from 30 to 100 or higher va=
lues depending on the skewness.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-22"><=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For non-normal data, the distribution of the sample variance may dev=
iate substantially from a <i>=CF=87</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"=
><sup>2</sup></span> distribution.
</p><p>However, if the sample size is large, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Slutsky%27s_theorem" title=3D"Slutsky's theorem">Slutsky's theor=
em</a> implies that the distribution of the sample variance has little effe=
ct on the distribution of the test statistic. That is, as sample size <span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math=
-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=
