x.php?title=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=
=3D"Edit section: Related statistical tests"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Alternatives_to_the_t-test_=
for_location_problems">Alternatives to the <i>t</i>-test for location probl=
ems</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStudent%=
27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Alter=
natives to the t-test for location problems"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <i>t</i>-test provides an exact test for the equality of the means o=
f two i.i.d. normal populations with unknown, but equal, variances. (<a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Welch%27s_t-test" title=3D"Welch's t-tes=
t">Welch's <i>t</i>-test</a> is a nearly exact test for the case where the =
data are normal but the variances may differ.)  For moderately large sample=
s and a one tailed test, the <i>t</i>-test is relatively robust to moderate=
 violations of the normality assumption.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sawilowsky-Blai=
r_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Studen=
t%27s_t-test#cite_note-Sawilowsky-Blair-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In large enough sam=
ples, the <i>t</i>-test asymptotically approaches the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-test" title=3D"Z-test"><i>z</i>-test</a>, and becomes=
 robust even to large deviations from normality.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_18-1=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_=
t-test#cite_note-:0-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>If the data are substantially non-normal and the sample size is smal=
l, the <i>t</i>-test can give misleading results. See <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Location_testing_for_Gaussian_scale_mixture_distributio=
ns" title=3D"Location testing for Gaussian scale mixture distributions">Loc=
ation test for Gaussian scale mixture distributions</a> for some theory rel=
ated to one particular family of non-normal distributions.
</p><p>When the normality assumption does not hold, a <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-parametric" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-para=
metric">non-parametric</a> alternative to the <i>t</i>-test may have better=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_power" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Statistical power">statistical power</a>. However, when da=
ta are non-normal with differing variances between groups, a <i>t</i>-test =
may have better <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_1_error" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Type 1 error">type-1 error</a> control than some=
 non-parametric alternatives.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-27"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Furthermore, non-parametric methods, such as the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test" title=3D"Mann=E2=80=93=
Whitney U test">Mann-Whitney U test</a> discussed below, typically do not t=
est for a difference of means, so should be used carefully if a difference =
of means is of primary scientific interest.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_18-2" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-tes=
t#cite_note-:0-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> For example, Mann-Whitney U test will keep t=
he type 1 error at the desired level alpha if both groups have the same dis=
tribution. It will also have power in detecting an alternative by which gro=
up B has the same distribution as A but after some shift by a constant (in =
which case there would indeed be a difference in the means of the two group=
s). However, there could be cases where group A and B will have different d=
istributions but with the same means (such as two distributions, one with p=
ositive skewness and the other with a negative one, but shifted so to have =
the same means). In such cases, MW could have more than alpha level power i=
n rejecting the Null hypothesis but attributing the interpretation of diffe=
rence in means to such a result would be incorrect.
</p><p>In the presence of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Outli=
er" title=3D"Outlier">outlier</a>, the <i>t</i>-test is not robust. For exa=
mple, for two independent samples when the data distributions are asymmetri=
c  (that is, the distributions are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Skewness" title=3D"Skewness">skewed</a>) or the distributions have large t=
ails, then the Wilcoxon rank-sum test (also known as the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mann%E2%80%93Whitney_U_test" title=3D"Mann=E2=80=93W=
hitney U test">Mann=E2=80=93Whitney <i>U</i> test</a>) can have three to fo=
ur times higher power than the <i>t</i>-test.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sawilowsky=
-Blair_26-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tudent%27s_t-test#cite_note-Sawilowsky-Blair-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stude=
nt%27s_t-test#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_no=
te-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> The nonparametric counterpart to the paired samples <i>t=
</i>-test is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilcoxon_signed-r=
ank_test" title=3D"Wilcoxon signed-rank test">Wilcoxon signed-rank test</a>=
 for paired samples. For a discussion on choosing between the <i>t</i>-test=
 and nonparametric alternatives, see Lumley, et al. (2002).<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-:0_18-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tudent%27s_t-test#cite_note-:0-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One-way <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_varianc=
e" title=3D"Analysis of variance">analysis of variance</a> (ANOVA) generali=
zes the two-sample <i>t</i>-test when the data belong to more than two grou=
ps.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"A_design_which_includes_bot=
h_paired_observations_and_independent_observations">A design which includes=
 both paired observations and independent observations</h3><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp;action=3D=
edit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: A design which includes both =
paired observations and independent observations"><span>edit</span></a><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>When both paired observations and independent observations are present i=
n the two sample design, assuming  data are missing completely at random (M=
CAR), the paired observations or independent observations may be discarded =
in order to proceed with the standard tests above. Alternatively making use=
 of all of the available data, assuming normality and MCAR, the generalized=
 partially overlapping samples <i>t</i>-test could be used.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Partover_30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Partover-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Multivariate_testing">Multi=
variate testing</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Multivariate testing"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotelling%27s_T-squa=
red_distribution" title=3D"Hotelling's T-squared distribution">Hotelling's =
T-squared distribution</a></div>
<p>A generalization of Student's <i>t</i> statistic, called <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotelling%27s_t-squared_statistic" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Hotelling's t-squared statistic">Hotelling's <i>t</i>-squa=
red statistic</a>, allows for the testing of hypotheses on multiple (often =
correlated) measures within the same sample. For instance, a researcher mig=
ht submit a number of subjects to a personality test consisting of multiple=
 personality scales (e.g. the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minn=
esota_Multiphasic_Personality_Inventory" title=3D"Minnesota Multiphasic Per=
sonality Inventory">Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory</a>). Becau=
se measures of this type are usually positively correlated, it is not advis=
able to conduct separate univariate <i>t</i>-tests to test hypotheses, as t=
hese would neglect the covariance among measures and inflate the chance of =
falsely rejecting at least one hypothesis (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Type_I_error" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Type I error">Type I =
error</a>). In this case a single multivariate test is preferable for hypot=
hesis testing. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher%27s_Method#L=
imitations_of_independent_assumption" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fisher=
's Method">Fisher's Method</a> for combining multiple tests with <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_I_and_type_II_errors#Type_I_error" t=
itle=3D"Type I and type II errors">alpha</a></i> reduced for positive corre=
lation among tests is one. Another is Hotelling's <i>T</i><span style=3D"pa=
dding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span> statistic follows a <i>T</i><span s=
tyle=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span> distribution. However, in=
 practice the distribution is rarely used, since tabulated values for <i>T<=
/i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span> are hard to fin=
d. Usually, <i>T</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></span=
> is converted instead to an <i>F</i> statistic.
</p><p>For a one-sample multivariate test, the hypothesis is that the mean =
vector (<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=CE=BC</b></span>) is equal to a given v=
ector (<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>=CE=BC</b><sub>0</sub></span>). The test =
statistic is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotelling%27s_t-squar=
ed_statistic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hotelling's t-squared statisti=
c">Hotelling's <i>t</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12em;"><sup>2</sup></s=
pan></a>:
</p>
