<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal"=
 title=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal">Learn how and when to remove t=
his message</a></small>)</i></span></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The two-sample <i>t</i>-test is a special case of simple <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_regression" title=3D"Linear regression">li=
near regression</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kutner2004_31-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Kutn=
er2004-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Walker2024_32-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Walker2024-32"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>33<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This relationship i=
s illustrated by the following example.
</p><p>A clinical trial examines 6 patients given drug or placebo. Three (3=
) patients get 0 units of drug (the placebo group). Three (3) patients get =
1 unit of drug (the active treatment group). At the end of treatment, the r=
esearchers measure the change from baseline in the number of words that eac=
h patient can recall in a memory test.
</p><p><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fi=
le:Graph_of_word_recall_vs_drug_dose.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><im=
g alt=3D"Scatter plot with six point. Three points on the left and are alig=
ned vertically at the drug dose of 0 units. And the other three points on t=
he right and are aligned vertically at the drug dose of 1 unit." src=3D"htt=
ps://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Graph_of_word_recall=
_vs_drug_dose.svg/330px-Graph_of_word_recall_vs_drug_dose.svg.png" decoding=
=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"197" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file=
-width=3D"375" data-file-height=3D"246"></a></span>
</p><p>A table of the patients' word recall and drug dose values are shown =
below.
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable">
<tbody><tr>
<th>Patient</th>
<th>drug.dose</th>
<th>word.recall
</th></tr>
<tr>
<th>1
</th>
<th>0
</th>
<td>1
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>2
</th>
<th>0
</th>
<td>2
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>3
</th>
<th>0
</th>
<td>3
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>4
</th>
<th>1
</th>
<td>5
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>5
</th>
<th>1
</th>
<td>6
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>6
</th>
<th>1
</th>
<td>7
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Data and code are given for the analysis using the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_programming_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
R programming language">R programming language</a> with the <code>t.test</c=
ode> and <code>lm</code>functions for the t-test and linear regression. Her=
e are the same (fictitious) data above generated in R.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-r mw-content-ltr" dir=3D"ltr">=
<pre><span></span><span class=3D"o">&gt;</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><s=
pan class=3D"n">word.recall.data</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><span cl=
ass=3D"nf">data.frame</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">dru=
g.dose</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><span class=3D"nf">c</span><span c=
lass=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"m">0</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><spa=
n class=3D"m">0</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"m">0</span><=
span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"m">1</span><span class=3D"p">,</spa=
n><span class=3D"m">1</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"m">1</=
span><span class=3D"p">),</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"n"=
>word.recall</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><span class=3D"nf">c</span><=
span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"m">1</span><span class=3D"p">,</spa=
n><span class=3D"m">2</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"m">3</=
span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"m">5</span><span class=3D"p">=
,</span><span class=3D"m">6</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"=
m">7</span><span class=3D"p">))</span>
</pre></div>
<p>Perform the <i>t</i>-test. Notice that the assumption of equal variance,=
 <code>var.equal=3DT</code>, is required to make the analysis exactly equiv=
alent to simple linear regression.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-r mw-content-ltr" dir=3D"ltr">=
<pre><span></span><span class=3D"o">&gt;</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><s=
pan class=3D"nf">with</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">wor=
d.recall.data</span><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><sp=
an class=3D"nf">t.test</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">wo=
rd.recall</span><span class=3D"o">~</span><span class=3D"n">drug.dose</span=
><span class=3D"p">,</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"n">var.=
equal</span><span class=3D"o">=3D</span><span class=3D"bp">T</span><span cl=
ass=3D"p">))</span>
</pre></div>
<p>Running the R code gives the following results.
</p>
<ul><li>The mean word.recall in the 0 drug.dose group is 2.</li>
<li>The mean word.recall in the 1 drug.dose group is 6.</li>
<li>The difference between treatment groups in the mean word.recall is 6 =
=E2=80=93 2 =3D 4.</li>
<li>The difference in word.recall between drug doses is significant (p=3D0.=
00805).</li></ul>
<p>Perform a linear regression of the same data. Calculations may be perfor=
med using the R function <code>lm()</code> for a linear model.=20
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-r mw-content-ltr" dir=3D"ltr">=
<pre><span></span><span class=3D"o">&gt;</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><s=
pan class=3D"n">word.recall.data.lm</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span c=
lass=3D"o">=3D</span><span class=3D"w">  </span><span class=3D"nf">lm</span=
><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">word.recall</span><span class=
=3D"o">~</span><span class=3D"n">drug.dose</span><span class=3D"p">,</span>=
<span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"n">data</span><span class=3D"o">=
=3D</span><span class=3D"n">word.recall.data</span><span class=3D"p">)</spa=
n>
<span class=3D"o">&gt;</span><span class=3D"w"> </span><span class=3D"nf">s=
ummary</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">word.recall.data.l=
m</span><span class=3D"p">)</span>
</pre></div>
<p>The linear regression provides a table of coefficients and p-values.
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable">
<tbody><tr>
<th>Coefficient</th>
<th>Estimate</th>
<th>Std. Error</th>
<th>t value</th>
<th>P-value
</th></tr>
<tr>
<th>Intercept
</th>
<th>2
</th>
<th>0.5774
</th>
<th>3.464
</th>
<td>0.02572
</td></tr>
<tr>
<th>drug.dose
</th>
<th>4
</th>
<th>0.8165
</th>
<th>4.899
</th>
<td>0.000805
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The table of coefficients gives the following results.
</p>
<ul><li>The estimate value of 2 for the intercept is the mean value of the =
word recall when the drug dose is 0.</li>
<li>The estimate value of 4 for the drug dose indicates that for a 1-unit c=
hange in drug dose (from 0 to 1) there is a 4-unit change in mean word reca=
ll (from 2 to 6). This is the slope of the line joining the two group means=
.</li>
<li>The p-value that the slope of 4 is different from 0 is p =3D 0.00805.</=
li></ul>
<p>The coefficients for the linear regression specify the slope and interce=
pt of the line that joins the two group means, as illustrated in the graph.=
 The intercept is 2 and the slope is 4.
</p><p><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fi=
le:Regression_lines_with_slopes_4_and_0.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description" =
title=3D"Regression lines"><img alt=3D"Regression lines" src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/b/bf/Regression_lines_with_slopes_4_and=
_0.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"263" class=3D"mw-file-el=
ement" data-file-width=3D"400" data-file-height=3D"263"></a></span>
</p><p>Compare the result from the linear regression to the result from the=
 <i>t</i>-test.
</p>
<ul><li>From the <i>t</i>-test, the difference between the group means is 6=
-2=3D4.</li>
<li>From the regression, the slope is also 4 indicating that a 1-unit chang=
e in drug dose (from 0 to 1) gives a 4-unit change in mean word recall (fro=
m 2 to 6).</li>
<li>The <i>t</i>-test <i>p</i>-value for the difference in means, and the r=
egression p-value for the slope, are both 0.00805. The methods give identic=
al results.</li></ul>
<p>This example shows that, for the special case of a simple linear regress=
ion where there is a single x-variable that has values 0 and 1, the <i>t</i=
>-test gives the same results as the linear regression. The relationship ca=
n also be shown algebraically.
</p><p>Recognizing this relationship between the <i>t</i>-test and linear r=
egression facilitates the use of multiple linear regression and multi-way <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analysis_of_variance" title=3D"Anal=
ysis of variance">analysis of variance</a>. These alternatives to <i>t</i>-=
tests allow for the inclusion of additional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Dependent_and_independent_variables" title=3D"Dependent and indep=
endent variables">explanatory variables</a>  that are associated with the r=
esponse. Including such additional explanatory variables using regression o=
r anova reduces the otherwise unexplained <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Variance">variance</a>, and commonly yields grea=
ter <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_of_a_test" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Power of a test">power</a> to detect differences than do =
two-sample <i>t</i>-tests.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Power_and_sample_size_for_t=
-tests">Power and sample size for t-tests</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DStudent%27s_t-test&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D24" title=3D"Edit section: Power and sample size for t-tests"><span>e=
dit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The power of a test is the probability that the test rejects the null hy=
pothesis when the alternative hypothesis is true.
</p><p>Power calculation for a two-sample t-test requires the following inf=
ormation
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Julious2010_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Student%27s_t-test#cite_note-Julious2010-37"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup>
</p>
<ul><li>The difference between the means of the two groups</li>
<li>The within-group standard deviation (if the two groups have the same st=
andard deviation)</li>
<li>The sample size (number of subjects) in each group</li>
<li>The required p-value (alpha) for significance</li></ul>
<p>To calculate power, it can be useful to compute the standardized effect =
size, which is the difference between the two means divided by the within-g=
roup standard deviation. For example, suppose that the mean of group A is 1=
4 and the mean of group B is 10, the within-group standard deviation is 8 u=
nits (assuming the two groups have the same standard deviation). Then the d=
ifference between group means is 14-10 =3D 4 units, and the standardized ef=
fect size is (14-10)/8 =3D 4/8 =3D 0.5.
</p><p>The graph below shows power for standardized effect sizes from 0.1 t=
o 1, for sample sizes per group from 10 to 50, assuming an equal number of =
subjects per group. N per group is the number of observations in each group=
. For example, for a standardized effect size of 0.5, a sample size of N =
=3D 10 per group gives power slightly less than 0.2, while a sample size of=
 N =3D 50 per group gives power of approximately 0.7.
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Power_vs_effect_size_and_sample_size.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"=
><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2e/Powe=
r_vs_effect_size_and_sample_size.svg/500px-Power_vs_effect_size_and_sample_=
size.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"400" height=3D"333" class=3D"mw-f=
ile-element" data-file-width=3D"382" data-file-height=3D"318"></a><figcapti=
on>Graph showing power of a two-sample t-test versus standardized effect si=
ze and sample size</figcaption></figure>
<p>Calculators for power and sample size are available at many websites, su=
ch as the following.
</p><p><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"https://homepage=
.univie.ac.at/robin.ristl/samplesize.php?test=3Dttest">https://homepage.uni=
vie.ac.at/robin.ristl/samplesize.php?test=3Dttest</a>
</p><p><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"https://www.stat=
ulator.com/SampleSize/ss2M.html">https://www.statulator.com/SampleSize/ss2M=
.html</a>
</p><p>Free software packages for power and sample size are described at th=
ese websites.
</p><p><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"https://stats.oa=
rc.ucla.edu/r/dae/power-analysis-for-two-group-independent-sample-t-test/">=
https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/r/dae/power-analysis-for-two-group-independent-=
sample-t-test/</a>
</p><p><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"https://stats.oa=
rc.ucla.edu/other/gpower/">https://stats.oarc.ucla.edu/other/gpower/</a>
</p><p><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"https://cqsclini=
cal.app.vumc.org/ps/">https://cqsclinical.app.vumc.org/ps/</a>
</p><p>Commercial software packages such as the following offer power and s=
ample size for t-tests and many other statistical tests.
</p><p><a rel=3D"nofollow" class=3D"external free" href=3D"https://www.ncss=
.com/software/pass/">https://www.ncss.com/software/pass/</a>
